args:
Mana returns to the dragon-vein spring, and
Su Fang starts producing pyroblossoms.
After a bit, however, Ku Hai claims something
is amiss at the spring, forcing the party to
rush out there once more.
We made it back, but what happened\nto Valfarre?!
Horrors! You can even hear it scream\nall the way in our world!
It is likely the beast's death knell.
Look! That fissure is closing!\nThat must mean Valfarre is beaten!
We are the best! We are the best!\nB-E-S-T! B-E-S-T!
Ooh hoo hoo! You young'uns really\nshowed this old fart a thing or two today.
The mana's returned. I reckon the spring\nwill be back to normal before long.
This means I can now make pyroblossoms!\nOh, what a relief...

I'm lookin' forward to 'em. Now then,
you young'uns head back to town and
make sure everything's ready for the
big Lunar New Year celebration!
What will you do, Peng Lai?
Oh, I'll stay here for a bit. Got a little\nsomethin' on my mind, so I do...
Don't you worry—I'll be sure to stop by\nin time for the big shindig!
Boy, this place is hopping now!
There are many people who return\nhere only for the Lunar New Year,\nincluding Xu Fu.
He's that Qilin tribe person who\nfounded this town, right?
Indeed. He lives a solitary life in the\nmountains, coming here but once a year.
In a way, this Lunar New Year festival\nalso serves as a kind of welcome-home\nparty for him.
No wonder this place is crammed to\nthe gills with folks!
It's getting me excited just looking at it!
It seems Su Fang's decision not to make a\nfuss about the problem was the right one.
Sure was. If they knew fiends had shown,\nmost'a these folks probably woulda turned\ntail and ran for the hills.
He was thinking about the town and the\npeople living in it all along.
Su Fang really does love Peng Lai.
If you'll excuse me. I have to finish up\nwith the pyroblossoms. Farewell.
Annnd...he's outta here.\nWhat's got his fireworks in a bunch?
Once, Su Fang was known as a man who\nwouldn't spare a thought for this town.\n...Er, or so I've heard.
Are we talking about the same Su Fang?
I myself have only heard rumors.\nApparently he focused on pyroblossoms\nand ignored all other issues.
Oh? If you're curious, perhaps we should\ngo ask his family about it.
I don't know. That seems like more of a\nbusybody thing than I'm comfortable with.
My master used to say, ＂Don't think, feel.＂\n...So I'LL go ask instead!
Ain't that sayin' about martial arts?
Shall we go then, Lin You?
Well, maybe we should tag along.\nI AM curious about this...
Well, it's true. The only thing that boy used\nto care a lick about was the quality of his\ngosh-darned pyroblossoms.

He worried about the color, the size...
everything! And he fought endlessly with
his parents, who were pyroblossom
technicians themselves.
Su Fang wanted to spread pyroblossoms\naround the world.
He wanted people everywhere to enjoy\nthem, not just those from his town.
But in order to achieve that goal,\nSu Fang ended up neglecting Peng Lai.
He worked on his pyroblossoms so much,\nhe refused to help with the Lunar New\nYear festival. Oh, his father was furious!
＂You have no idea what the most important\nthing about pyroblossoms is,＂ he said.
＂No matter how showy or massive they\nmight be, your current work is a failure.\nNo one will ever enjoy them.＂
That day, Su Fang left the village.
He actually ran away from home?
Apparently he went to other villages\nand set off his pyroblossoms there.
Trying to prove his father wrong,\nI imagine.
I suspect that's what he was intending.\nAnd while I don't know what happened\nin those other towns...
When Su Fang finally returned home,\nhis parents had passed.
They perished in a pyroblossom accident,\nand their workshop burned to the ground.
Ever since, Su Fang has been a different\nperson—one totally devoted to the town.

While we're delighted to see the people of
the town rely on him, we also can't help
but think the boy may be denying himself
a chance at his dreams.
I worry that we and this town have\nbecome a burden for him to bear.
My apologies for making you all listen\nto such a shameful tale.
As you heard, far from valuing my town,\nI was something of a troublemaker.
But that was a long time ago, right?
Not so long. And at any rate, I am still the\nsame person deep down. It reminds me\nof something my father once said to me...
＂No one wants to come back to a town\nwhere you're launching pyroblossoms.＂
Yet even now, I continue to rebel\nagainst his words.
I'm working to build excitement among\nthe people for the Lunar New Year\nand draw big crowds to this town.
It makes me so happy to see their faces\nlight up at my work. And yet...
I also feel like I'm doing it specifically\nto spite my father. Or his memory, I guess.
You must come to the dragon-vein spring!\nThere's trouble!
Don't worry, Grandmother.\nThese people are trustworthy.

I know both of you feel that you—
and indeed, the entire town—are a
burden on me, but it is not the case.
I will never give up on my dreams.

But I couldn't bring myself to leave town
again without understanding what my
father said was the most important thing
about pyroblossoms.
And I feel like I'm finally realizing that\ntruth thanks to these fine people here.
I'll be back, I promise. We have the\nLunar New Year to think about, after all!
